[1] Cholera - Japan
Date: Mon, 21 Feb 2005
From: Mikio Kimura <kimumiki@nih.go.jp>


Under the Japanese Infectious Disease Control Law enacted in Apr 1999,
cases are allocated based on the date of diagnosis, but not that of disease
onset. In the case of cholera, not only symptomatic, laboratory-confirmed
cases, but asymptomatic and suspected cases should also be reported. Thus,
the number of reported cholera cases was 58 in 2000, 50 in 2001, 51 in
2002, and 25 in 2003; however, it rose to 82 cases in 2004.

For 2004, excluding 6 suspected cases, the presumed country of disease
acquisition was Japan in 11 cases, and foreign countries in 65 cases, 33 of
which were the Philippines. When re-allocated by the date of disease onset,
those presumed to have been contracted in the Philippines were clustered
during Jul-Sep 2004. The serotype of isolates from all the Philippine cases
was O1 Ogawa, except for 1 case that was not typed.

A formal outbreak investigation was not carried out; instead, our FETP
[field epidemiology training programme? - Mod.SH] team made inquiries
through the prefecture health departments, especially about the regions of
the Philippines visited and the possible connections between the cases. Our
FETP team also shared the patientsï¿½ information with the Philippine FETP
and the Philippine National Epidemiology Center. Many of the 33 cases
stayed in Manila or the neighboring areas, and some others visited remote
islands. Several cases traveled together: however, most of the cases
traveled independently. Thus, no particular recommendations other than
personal hygiene could be drawn to avoid infection for travelers from
Japan. Since Oct 2004, the number of cholera cases presumed to be of
Philippine origin appears to be at a baseline level.

--
Mikio Kimura MD
Infectious Disease Surveillance Center
National Institute of Infectious Diseases
Tokyo, Japan
<kimumiki@nih.go.jp>

[ProMED-mail thanks Dr Kimura for this information. - Mod. LL]

