[2] Cholera - Mozambique (Sofala)
Date: Wed, 23 Feb 2005
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: All Africa.com [edited]
<http://allafrica.com/stories/200502220961.html>


Cholera outbreak confirmed in Sofala
------------------------------------
The health authorities in the central Mozambican province of Sofala
diagnosed (on Mon 21 Feb 2005) 19 new cases of cholera, following a report
of a case of diarrhea in Marromeu district last Wed, 16 Feb 2005, that was
later confirmed as cholera. Provincial chief doctor Flavio Wate, cited in
an issue of the Maputo daily "Noticias", said that 1 case was diagnosed in
Beira, while the others were all reported from Marromeu.

"In Marromeu, the cholera outbreak was notified in the resettlement center
for the victims of floods in the last 2 years, in the locality of Nensa. We
believe that poor supply of drinking water and poor individual and
collective hygiene on the part of some of the residents may lie at the
origin of the outbreak. So far, 18 cases have been diagnosed in Marromeu,
15 of them in Nensa, and the rest in Marromeu town", said Wate.

Schoolteachers in the district have received a 1-day course on cholera
prevention. There were 3 earlier confirmed cases of cholera in Sofala in
2005, 2 in Beira, and 1 in Dondo district.

The Sofala health authorities are also monitoring the districts of Dondo
and Nhamatanda. In the latter district cases of severe diarrhea, which
might prove to be cholera, have been notified.

