[5] Cholera - Congo DR (South Kivu)
Date: Thu, 24 Feb 2005
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: International Federation of Red Cross And Red Crescent Societies
(IFRC)
<http://www.reliefweb.int/rw/RWB.NSF/db900SID/JWIN-69WHGT?OpenDocument>


Cholera in South Kivu
---------------------
Since 23 Dec 2004, a series of heavy rainstorms has battered the town of
Uvira in South Kivu province of eastern DRC. The most devastating storm was
on 8 Feb 2005, resulting in 8 deaths (6 children and 2 adults) and 3
wounded; 900 houses were either partially or entirely destroyed, resulting
in 5386 people (1095 children and 4291 adults) being left without shelter.
These rains also damaged the 3 main bridges in the area; it is feared that
their weakened state may cause them to collapse, potentially isolating the
entire southern part of South Kivu.

The rains and ensuing flooding have damaged latrines, allowing human fecal
matter to escape; this has exposed the inhabitants to the risk of
water-source contamination and a rapid spreading of cholera. Indeed, this
is already the case in Uvira, as well as Bukavu. As of 30 Jan 2005, a total
of over 2379 cholera cases have been reported, with 23 deaths (1 per cent
mortality). The epidemic is predominantly active in Bukavu and Uvira: from
17-30 Jan 2005, 90 per cent of 582 reported cases were from this province.
The current average in Bukavu is 10 new cases each day; most are coming
from neighboring villages.

There are 3 main causes for this outbreak:
- poor access to potable water, resulting in the population resorting to
drinking water from rivers and lakes; a UNICEF survey (2001) indicated only
17.3 per cent of people with access to potable water within 15 minutes.
- inadequate basic hygiene practices;
- inadequate access to latrines (the same UNICEF survey showed only 40 per
cent of the population with access).

